Analyze liveness from bottom to top:

Line 10: return d+f     uses: d, f;   after: {}
  before: {d, f}

Line 9: d = 5 + e       def: d; uses: e;   after: {d,f}
  before: {e, f}  (d killed, e and f needed)

Line 8: e = b + f       def: e; uses: b, f;  after: {e, f}
  before: {b, f}  (e killed, b and f needed)

Line 7: b = c + e       def: b; uses: c, e;  after: {b, f}
  before: {c, e, f}  (b killed, c e f needed)

Line 6: f = c + e       def: f; uses: c, e;  after: {c, e, f}
  before: {c, e}  (f killed, c e needed)
  Wait: after line 6 is {c, e, f} (since b=c+e still uses c and e).
  Before line 6: need c, e (to compute f=c+e), and f is being defined (not yet live before this line).
  So before line 6: {c, e}.
  But AFTER line 6: f is live (used in lines 8,9,10), c is live (used in line 7), e is live (used in lines 7,8).
  Live AFTER line 6 = {c, e, f}. Maximum here is 3.

Line 5: e = c + d       def: e; uses: c, d;  after: {c, e, f}... wait f not defined yet.
  Redo: work strictly backward.

Live after line 10 (return d+f): {} (nothing needed after return)
Before line 10: uses d,f -> {d, f}

Before line 9 (d=5+e): Live after = {d,f}; def=d, use=e -> {e,f}
Before line 8 (e=b+f): Live after = {e,f}; def=e, use=b,f -> {b,f}
Before line 7 (b=c+e): Live after = {b,f}; def=b, use=c,e -> {c,e,f}  [MAX=3]
Before line 6 (f=c+e): Live after = {c,e,f}; def=f, use=c,e -> {c,e}   [still need c,e; f defined here]
  Actually before line 6: {c,e} plus whatever was live after and not killed: f is defined in line 6 so f is NOT live before line 6. So before line 6: {c, e}.
Before line 5 (e=c+d): Live after = {c,e}; def=e, use=c,d -> {c,d}
Before line 4 (d=a+b): Live after = {c,d}; def=d, use=a,b -> {a,b,c}  [MAX=3]
